##Swiss lawmaker kicked out of parliament for wearing a mask! How to understand Europe without a mask?

Micro Signal China Business Journal

Function introduction, grow in step with Chinese enterprises, talk with business leaders, spread business ideals, serve business people, "China Business News" control of the absolute voice of Chinese business.

New Crown Pneumonia epidemic period, less travel, frequent hand washing, wearing masks have been deeply engraved in the minds of the Chinese people. However, in the spread of the epidemic in Europe, wearing masks instead become alien, may be "discrimination. ".

The congresswoman was ejected from the chamber for wearing a mask

According to the latest data released by the Italian Ministry of Health at 18:00 local time on March 3, there are 2,263 cases of new coronaviruses in Italy, 79 deaths, 160 cures, and a total of 2,502 confirmed cases of new coronaviruses, there were 466 new cases, including 229 severe cases and 27 new deaths.

The local health department's advice to all citizens remains: "Do not wear a mask if you are not ill. ".

On February 26th an Italian MP entered parliament wearing a mask, only to be mocked for it. During the speech, he was emotional, took off his mask, and told everyone, "I have been to three epidemic areas, wearing a mask is for everyone's safety, if you are smart people, you would have put on a mask, " and finished, he slammed the microphone angrily.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)

A similar situation has occurred in Switzerland.

On 3 March, a Swiss congresswoman attending a meeting of the Federal Council was expelled from the Chamber for insisting on wearing a mask.

![img](data:image/jpeg;base64,)
Photograph: The glimpses

Swiss media reported that the People's Party Brauch was the only person wearing a mask that day, the speaker of the National Assembly of the Swiss Federal Parliament that the move disturbed the order of the meeting, asked him to take off his mask or leave the venue. Brauch expressed confusion and refused to take off his mask. After consultation, she was allowed to enter the room at the time of the vote. The member said the move was made to avoid infection or transmission to others.

Switzerland is one of the world's 20 most severely affected countries by the new coronavirus. According to Swiss media reports, as of 8:00 local time on the 4th, Switzerland confirmed a total of 58 cases, 2 cases were discharged. The Swiss federal government announced last week that it would cancel large gatherings of more than 1,000 people at least until March 15. The government also requires people to follow the following rules: 1. Avoid shaking hands or hugging while greeting; 2. Dispose of used tissues in an airtight dustbin; 3. If there are symptoms to contact the state and city emergency contact phone, explain the situation before going to the emergency room.

Healthy people don't need masks in Europe

In fact, not only Italy and Switzerland do not recommend wearing face masks, including France, Germany, the United Kingdom and other governments issued an official epidemic prevention manual issued by the recommendation is basically similar: Do not need.

On the whole, these European country's epidemic prevention manual all followed WHO's recommendation, it emphasizes washing hands frequently, covering your arms when coughing or sneezing, using disposable tissues, avoiding handshakes and unnecessary physical contact.

The NHS says masks are important in places such as hospitals, but there is little evidence that covering the nose and mouth with a mask reduces the risk of contracting the new coronavirus in healthy people. The main function of masks is to prevent patients from spreading the disease to others, so those who have symptoms need to wear masks.

The Italian Health Ministry, citing the World Health Organization organisation, said masks should be worn only by people who may have come in contact with the patient, those who have had symptoms such as coughing or sneezing, and those who are caring for suspected or confirmed patients, and the medical staff at the hospital. In addition, people should wear masks in Romagné, Florida, Lombardy and Veneto, the red areas of northern Italy.

Germany's Health Ministry said that the general population wearing masks "does not make sense" , should focus on the epidemic prevention of personal hygiene. Wearing a mask in the right way (a bearded man, for example, needs to shave first) and changing it frequently is the only way to reduce the risk of infection. Wearing a mask can also create a false sense of security and lead to the neglect of other hygiene measures, such as frequent hand washing. The Ministry of Health recommends that people with flu-related symptoms talk to their family doctor before deciding whether, how and which type of mask to wear.

The French Ministry of Health recommends wearing a mask if you have visited a specific area in the past two weeks, such as China, Singapore, North Korea, Iran and northern Italy. However, it is emphasized that respirators with suction valves, such as FFP2, should be left to medical personnel.

Local Chinese: Wearing or not wearing a mask is a problem

Chinese in Europe are somewhat embarrassed by the advice that "healthy people don't need to wear masks" : wearing masks for fear of being considered "sick" and not for fear of contracting the virus.

Li Jiayue, a 40 year old native of Wenzhou, arrived in Italy in May 2000, the Qianjiang Evening News reported. He and his wife, Herceau, then co-founded the Marche International Chinese school in The Marches 见 Marche，Reg. . The area is known for its industry, with more than 40,000 overseas Chinese in the area, most of whom are engaged in shoe bag processing.

"The new pneumonia in Italy is getting worse and worse, and people are getting nervous. There is no big problem with the daily necessities, mainly because the Italian government's policy is in conflict with our Chinese people's awareness of protection. From the beginning of the outbreak, the Chinese have been stressing the need to wear masks, to travel less and to suspend work and school. But the Italian government has a different policy for preventing and controlling the epidemic. They say, 'masks are for sick people, and the new coronavirus is only a little more dangerous than the flu. There is no need to stop work and school, ' " Li said, this has caused local Chinese distress: Go out wearing a mask, or do not wear a mask.

On March 2, local time in Italy, Wenzhou Overseas Chinese, italy-china Youth Federation President Zheng Zaisheng shopping in a shopping mall in Florence, see the Italians do not wear masks, he will not wear, put the mask in his pocket. "Many Italians here don't wear masks, and Chinese are criticized for wearing masks, " said Zheng, who trades in imports and exports and whose business and life have been affected by the outbreak.

Shao Shengdong, an overseas Chinese from Wenzhou, lives in Rome. At present, 7 cases of new coronary pneumonia have been confirmed in his Lazio district. "I'm a little flustered. At present, the Italian government's preventive measures against the epidemic are not unified. Whether ordinary people should wear masks is one of the most vexed questions at present. Now we Chinese are in a dilemma. Some time ago I had some masks on hand, but now the epidemic is serious and masks are tight,"Shao said, all he can do now is to protect himself and his family. Besides, his clothing store business has been badly affected, and he hasn't had many customers lately.

It is worth noting that many Chinese living in Italy, France and the United Kingdom said that face masks are already hard to find in brick-and-mortar pharmacies, and online stores often show a shortage of them, if you want to buy a mask, you have to go through the Chinese community "self-seeking channels. ".

Sources: Daily Economic News, Qianjiang Evening News, Global Network, Interface News, etc.
